scrolly-map.Copy: Before the invasion, Russian or Russian-supported forces controled Crimea and parts of Donetsk and Luhansk.
Two weeks into the war, Russian forces were just a handful of miles from the capital city Kyiv.
But a month later, this threat was reduced. Ukraine performed its first successful counteroffensive in the north of the country, when Russian forces were pushed away from Kyiv.
Since then, further counterattacks pushed the Russians away from the northern city of Kharkiv in September.

And then the regional capital of the illegally annexed Kherson in November. While much of the region's land is still in Russian hands, this was the only regional capital Russia had seized and was a big blow to lose it.
Now, one year on, the two sides are locked in stalemate. Russian forces have once again made a few gains in Donetsk, with fighting centred on Bakhmut, but these gains have come at a high cost.

scrolly-chart.Header: Russia retreats from Kyiv in April
scrolly-chart.Copy: After an initial rush on capital Kyiv fails, Russian forces retreated from north.
Russia’s focus on the east slowly worked, with territory gains in Luhansk and Donetsk.
Through most of summer 2022, an uneasy stalemate ensued with both sides unable to break through.
This changed in early September, when Ukrainian forces liberated the vast majority of Kharkiv region.
Ukraine won another key victory in liberating Kherson city. While Russia still controlled the majority of the region's land, the capital was home to over a quarter of its pre-war population.

scrolly-chart.Header: Winter stalemate with heavy Donetsk fighting
scrolly-chart.Copy: Now, the fronlines remain static with the exception of some grinding Russian gains in Donetsk at high cost to both sides of the war.
